In the beginning there was everything
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's easier to write this down in the first person; none of the messy indirect
 speech stuff.
 None of the `he did that and then had he'.
 No.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First of all, nothing happened at that time.
 Even though there was everything.
 Does that make any sense? Allow me to more fully explain.
 Hopefully, by the end of the book it will have made just enough sense to
 keep reading, and just enough nonsense to get published.
 At least, if that's how publishers work in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because I'm from the past.
 Don't try and calculate when it is I'm talking about.
 I've always been from the past.
 See, I was there, right from the beginning.
 I saw how it all went down.
 I saw the tiniest of things in the smallest of space and all that crap
 those folks that call themselves scientists believe in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That's right, it's a belief.
 And I'm telling you, I saw all that and believe me if you will, and laugh
 at me if you won't but it was nothing like these folks have been thinking
 it was like.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was everything.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I know it's hard to explain.
 That's another reason I'm writing this all down.
 Also, I reckon it's quite important.
 I've heard talk that some have attempted this before, with a varying degree
 of success.
 Before I go any further, I should remind you I wasn't alive all the time
 in between, so there might be some dark spots.
 Places and names could be important, but then again it's only one version
 of events.
 What matters is..
 How it all matters, don't you see?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I guess you don't.
 I guess you will.
 That's why my life is out of love.
